00:41:16.400 --> 00:41:17.700
as revolutionary participants.

00:41:17.700 --> 00:41:21.050
That's what makes the situation
of [foreign word] so important is

00:41:21.050 --> 00:41:22.790
that she actually demanded it,

00:41:22.790 --> 00:41:25.400
as a veteran of the
revolution, as a soldadera.

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:28.350
No? So, they took all
kinds of different roles.

00:41:28.350 --> 00:41:32.560
They were often spies,
smugglers and strategists.

00:41:32.560 --> 00:41:34.110
So, they took on different roles.

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:35.900
And then some were just simply
cooks, and they were able

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:39.280
to market themselves as through
their culinary expertise,

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:41.150
their ability to make
a lot out of nothing.

00:41:41.150 --> 00:41:44.960
Because they handle the
soldada, the soldier's money,

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:46.260
and were able to purchase
provisions.

00:41:46.260 --> 00:41:49.230
Remember there was no
commissary or even infirmary.

00:41:49.230 --> 00:41:51.560
So, that's what the
roles of soldaderas did.

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:56.560
With regards to the first
comment on blacks in Mexico.

00:41:56.560 --> 00:42:02.260
Yes, Mexico was I think the
second country to abolish slavery.

00:42:02.260 --> 00:42:05.360
The second president of the
Mexican Republic after independence

00:42:05.360 --> 00:42:08.280
from Spain was an Afro Mexican.

00:42:08.280 --> 00:42:09.580
I mean people don't know that.

00:42:09.580 --> 00:42:11.480
They get whitened later on.

00:42:11.480 --> 00:42:14.860
One of the primary revolutionary
leaders was [foreign name]

00:42:14.860 --> 00:42:19.920
and he was also not
from [foreign word].

00:42:19.920 --> 00:42:23.280
And during the colony period, I
think what your father was eluding

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:27.120
to was there was a very
prominent working class.

00:42:27.120 --> 00:42:29.130
Freed, black class.

00:42:29.130 --> 00:42:32.630
Why? Because slavery lasted
a generation or two at most.

00:42:32.630 --> 00:42:35.690
There was certainly the
chattel plantation model,

00:42:35.690 --> 00:42:37.520
which is what we think of
when we think of slavery,

00:42:37.520 --> 00:42:39.300
these big cotton plantations.

00:42:39.300 --> 00:42:42.230 position:56%
In Mexico it would've been sugar,
tobacco, [foreign word], and mining,

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:45.240
but they were also
petaled off slavery,

00:42:45.240 --> 00:42:50.330
a slave could often acquire the
official, you know, of his master

00:42:50.330 --> 00:42:53.040
and the master often freed
him in his own lifetime.

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:54.580
And the children were
often godchildren.

00:42:54.580 --> 00:42:56.530
So, there's this patronage,
of course,

00:42:56.530 --> 00:42:58.150
but they were often
freed in their lifetime.

00:42:58.150 --> 00:43:00.150
So, it would last a
generation or two at most.

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:03.360
And there was an urban class,
it was an urban phenomenon.

00:43:03.360 --> 00:43:07.170
Mexico City had more blacks than
it did Spaniards at one point.

00:43:07.170 --> 00:43:08.800
In part because of slavery.

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:12.180
But it's this particularized,
sort of localized slavery;

00:43:12.180 --> 00:43:14.260
fruit sellers, the shoemaker.

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:16.910
I mean so they turned
into a vibrant class

00:43:16.910 --> 00:43:20.430
that then became Hispanicized
really early on.

00:43:20.430 --> 00:43:21.890
And so, they mixed
in really early on.

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:23.650
So, there's an insistence
on phenotype.

00:43:23.650 --> 00:43:25.770
They said, well we don't
really have what looks

00:43:25.770 --> 00:43:28.250
like Brazil or Cuba here in Mexico.

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:30.900
Thus, we don't really have an
important black population.

00:43:30.900 --> 00:43:32.940
But it mixed in really early on.

00:43:32.940 --> 00:43:35.020
And so, the slave trade
was abrogated very early

00:43:35.020 --> 00:43:36.700
on in Mexico as well.

00:43:36.700 --> 00:43:39.160
And they had rights
because of Canon Law.

00:43:39.160 --> 00:43:40.460
Because of the pope.

00:43:40.460 --> 00:43:41.760
So, they were able
to appeal the rights.

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:44.580
I'm not saying that slavery
wasn't horrible in Mexico.

00:43:44.580 --> 00:43:47.580
But what I am saying is that they
had a little more liberty to appeal

00:43:47.580 --> 00:43:51.080
through the church, through the
mechanisms of the church to appeal

00:43:51.080 --> 00:43:58.010
to have regular families and to get
Sundays off and stay in the cities.

00:43:58.010 --> 00:44:02.630
Or, they mixed in with indigenous
populations, which is understudied.

00:44:02.630 --> 00:44:05.120
In part because there was,

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:06.780
in colonial Mexico [speaking
in foreign language].

00:44:06.780 --> 00:44:11.020
Many times blacks would escape
to the indigenous communities.

00:44:11.020 --> 00:44:12.820
And then they were
no longer accounted.

00:44:12.820 --> 00:44:18.600 position:56%
And the last part about that is that
blacks also, there was no census.

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:25.790
Because of that sort of viciousness
with regards to the caste system.

00:44:25.790 --> 00:44:29.970
The [foreign word], the
second president abrogated,

00:44:29.970 --> 00:44:33.650 position:56%
he also eliminated the caste system,
so that they would all be Mexicans,

00:44:33.650 --> 00:44:38.910
but then unfortunately eliminated
the record of blacks in Mexico.

00:44:38.910 --> 00:44:45.160
So thus, the invisibility
for 200 years until now.

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:47.500
Yes. What's your name?

00:44:47.500 --> 00:44:49.470
&gt;&gt; Desiree.

00:44:49.470 --> 00:44:56.970
Hi. Thank you so much
for this [inaudible].

00:44:56.970 --> 00:45:08.560
Can you give us a sense of what
the relationship was between middle

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:12.200
and upper class women who
kind of busied themselves

00:45:12.200 --> 00:45:20.830 position:56%
with like legal equity and feminism,
feminist work, and the soldadera.

00:45:20.830 --> 00:45:23.570
&gt;&gt; Christina Arce: Oh, during
the revolutionary period?

00:45:23.570 --> 00:45:25.550
Oh, that's a great question.

00:45:25.550 --> 00:45:29.110
Because there's a lot; not
a lot, but more written

00:45:29.110 --> 00:45:35.150
on precisely the upper class women
who; I mean the first battle cry

00:45:35.150 --> 00:45:38.280
of the Mexican revolution, which
preceded the Cuban Revolution,

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:39.980
preceded the Russian Revolution,

00:45:39.980 --> 00:45:43.190
was actually at an upper-class
woman's house [foreign word]

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:44.490
in northern Mexico.

00:45:44.490 --> 00:45:51.150 position:56%
So, they had a real important role,
in part because they were completely

00:45:51.150 --> 00:45:53.680
on the outside of Mexican society.

00:45:53.680 --> 00:45:55.200
So, because of the dictatorship

00:45:55.200 --> 00:45:57.820
of the paternalistic
patriarchal society.

00:45:57.820 --> 00:45:59.840
So, women in particular
upper-class women; so,

00:45:59.840 --> 00:46:04.240
there has been some scholarship,
particularly, Mexican scholars

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:08.840
and North American scholars have
focused a lot on that relationship.

00:46:08.840 --> 00:46:13.850
Also, soldaderas were not looked
upon, they sort of like presented

00:46:13.850 --> 00:46:16.450
as this degenerate femininity.

00:46:16.450 --> 00:46:19.670
So, there was certainly
class tensions.

00:46:19.670 --> 00:46:21.930
One of the most important; so,
they would not have taken nicely

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:23.230
to being called soldaderas.

00:46:23.230 --> 00:46:29.640
You know, because it was sort of
a pejorative way to call some sort

00:46:29.640 --> 00:46:34.220
of trashy women who
followed the troops right.

00:46:34.220 --> 00:46:38.980
It was almost like calling
them a prostitute, right?

00:46:38.980 --> 00:46:43.160
Whereas adelita acquired this
short of sweetheart intonation.

00:46:43.160 --> 00:46:45.470
So, definitely, I mean, but one

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:47.580
of the most important figures
[foreign name] who wrote a book

00:46:47.580 --> 00:46:52.940
that was not published
in her lifetime.

00:46:52.940 --> 00:46:57.000
She went broke supporting
the revolution,

00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:59.170
she founded the White
Cross in Mexico.

00:46:59.170 --> 00:47:02.030
And was one of the primary
advisors to the [foreign word]

00:47:02.030 --> 00:47:05.500
who became president
afterwards regime.

00:47:05.500 --> 00:47:11.880
She was completely
unrecognized up until 20 years ago

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:16.870 position:56%
when [foreign name] recovered her
book that was rejected over 20 times

00:47:16.870 --> 00:47:20.960
by different editorials in
Mexico and in the United States.

00:47:20.960 --> 00:47:24.100
She wrote her book in
Spanish and English.

00:47:24.100 --> 00:47:25.450
And is called [foreign
word], the rebel.

00:47:25.450 --> 00:47:30.200
And so, certainly she talks about,
she oftentimes will be disinclined

00:47:30.200 --> 00:47:33.650
to call the female
companion soldaderas.

00:47:33.650 --> 00:47:35.760
She'll call them, you know,
the nurse, or something else.

00:47:35.760 --> 00:47:37.060
[Foreign name], did the same.

00:47:37.060 --> 00:47:39.970
She wrote a beautiful set of short
stories on the Mexican Revolution

00:47:39.970 --> 00:47:44.300 position:56%
and she also, in a such a subsequent
revision took the word soldadera out

00:47:44.300 --> 00:47:46.660
and replace it with
woman or muchacha, no?

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:48.100
Because I mean in a way to
not reduce into that level.

00:47:48.100 --> 00:47:49.400
So, they were very much,
there's a distinction

00:47:49.400 --> 00:47:50.700
between those class levels,

00:47:50.700 --> 00:47:52.000
yet women of upper-classes
joined the revolutionary forces,

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:53.300
were often strategists.

00:47:53.300 --> 00:47:54.600
[Foreign name] had a
female strategist and orator

00:47:54.600 --> 00:47:55.900
that wrote five books on
the Mexican Revolution.

00:47:55.900 --> 00:47:58.200
None of that is recognized.

